# Knowledge Base Page Authoring

When creating or editing pages in this mdBook (`docs/`), read `docs/introduction.md` first and calibrate tone, depth, and assumed prerequisites to the author’s profile.

## Reader profile (from introduction)

- **Education:** BS electrical engineering (University of Tehran); PhD and two MS degrees from UW–Madison (ECE and physics).
- **Research background:** Quantum transport and nanostructures; exciton transfer in carbon nanotubes; thermoelectric nanowires; quantum state evolution; cleanroom fabrication (sputtering, amorphous-silicon transistors).
- **Industry:** Statistical methods for circuit modeling at Intel; prior reliability modeling and production data analysis; software engineering (Google).
- **Current site topics:** Circuit simulation (SPICE, MNA, stamping), spacetime geometry, condensed-matter and device physics.

**Default audience:** The author revisiting a topic — a working physicist/engineer with solid graduate-level QM, statistical mechanics, solid-state physics, and numerical methods. Not a textbook for undergraduates; not a research monograph with full proofs.

## Voice and tone

- First-person is optional; neutral technical voice is fine.
- “Messy notebook energy” — working notes, not a polished textbook chapter.
- Direct, precise prose. No filler intros (“In this section we will…”).
- Connect theory to devices, transport, or computation when natural (the author’s instinct is application-aware).

## Structure

1. **Opening paragraph** — what the concept is and why it matters in one or two sentences.
2. **Sections** with `##` headings; subsections with `###` when needed.
3. **Close with links** to related pages in this repo when they exist (relative markdown links).
4. Add the page to `docs/SUMMARY.md` under the appropriate section.

## Math and notation

- Use `$...$` for inline math and `$$...$$` for display equations (mdBook/KaTeX).
- State conventions explicitly (metric signature, units, natural units, Fourier conventions) when they affect signs or factors of 2π.
- Skip elementary derivations the reader already knows (e.g. basic Schrödinger equation, KCL). Spend depth on the non-obvious step or the physical insight.
- Prefer standard physics/EE notation consistent with existing pages (`η_{μν}`, `G_{μν}`, MNA matrix blocks, etc.).

## Visual aids

- Use **tables** for comparisons, regimes, or symbol glossaries.
- Use **mermaid** diagrams for flow, hierarchy, or phase diagrams when a figure clarifies structure (see `docs/physics/minkowski-space.md`).
- Do not add images unless the user provides assets or explicitly requests them.

## Depth calibration

| Topic area | Assumed known | Emphasize |
|------------|---------------|-----------|
| Condensed matter / transport | Fermi surface, bands, scattering, second quantization basics | Many-body mechanisms, measurable signatures, nanoscale limits |
| Circuit simulation | KCL/KVL, linear algebra, basic device models | Matrix structure, stamping, numerical stability |
| Relativity / GR | Special relativity, tensors at a first-course level | Geometric meaning, index gymnastics, field equations |
| Statistical / ML methods | Probability, estimation, linear models | Assumptions, failure modes, connection to physical models |

When a topic spans areas (e.g. superconducting qubits), bridge from solid-state physics toward circuits or numerics as the author would.

## Prerequisites and scope

- List **Prerequisites** only when the page genuinely needs specific prior pages or courses; keep the list short.
- State **Scope / out of scope** when the topic is large (e.g. “BCS mean-field only; no full Eliashberg numerics”).
- Point to standard references (textbooks, review papers) sparingly — one line is enough.

## What to avoid

- Tutorial tone aimed at beginners with no physics background.
- Exhaustive literature reviews or historical surveys unless requested.
- Duplicating content that already exists on another page — link instead.
- Creating markdown files outside `docs/` for book content (except Cursor rules in `.cursor/rules/`).
- Changing `book.toml`, theme, CI, or deployment config unless the task requires it.

## File conventions

- Path: `docs/<section>/<slug>.md` (e.g. `docs/physics/bcs-superconductivity.md`).
- Filename: lowercase, hyphen-separated.
- Title: `# Title Case or Sentence case` matching existing pages (title case for named concepts: “Minkowski Space”, “Modified Nodal Analysis”).

## Checklist before finishing

- [ ] Page added to `docs/SUMMARY.md`
- [ ] Math renders (balanced `$`/`$$`, no broken LaTeX)
- [ ] At least one cross-link to a related page if applicable
- [ ] Depth matches graduate physicist/engineer, not intro undergraduate
